  <statement>
    <p>TRAPPIST-1e is an exoplanet that orbits the star TRAPPIST-1.
      The exoplanet orbits the star on a roughly circular orbit at a distance of
      <quantity><value>0.029</value><unit>astronomical_unit</unit></quantity>.</p>
  </statement>
  <mcq standalone="true">
    <stem>
      <p>Does TRAPPIST-1e orbit its star at a smaller or at a larger orbital radius than 
        Earth’s orbital radius around the Sun?</p>
    </stem>
    <key fixed_order="1">A smaller orbital radius</key>
    <distractor d="1" fixed_order="2">
     A larger orbital radius
    </distractor>
  </mcq>
  <mcq standalone="true">
    <stem>
      <p>Use the formula <latex>$@T = \sqrt{\frac{4 @pi^{2} @r^{3}}{@G@M}}$</latex>, where <latex>$@r$</latex> 
        is the radius of the exoplanet’s orbit, <latex>$@M$</latex>
        is the mass of the host star, and <latex>$@G$</latex> is the universal gravitational constant, to find <latex>$@T$</latex>,
        the period of the exoplanet’s orbit. TRAPPIST-1 has a mass of <latex>$<quantity><value>1.8 \times 10^{29}</value><unit>kilogram</unit></quantity>$</latex>.
        Use a value of <latex>$<quantity><value>6.67 \times 10^{-11}</value><unit>meter^3 per kilogram second^2</unit></quantity>$</latex> for <latex>$@G$</latex>. 
        Give your answer in <quantity type="long"><value></value><unit>day</unit></quantity>
         to two decimal places.</p>
    </stem>
